# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: egg-hunt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In 1896, Housman published *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of poems marked by the author's pessimism and preoccupation with early death, which gradually acquired a wide readership and appealed particularly to a younger audience during World War I.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Another collection, entitled *Last Poems*, appeared in 1922.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry became popular for musical settings.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Following his death, further poems from his notebooks were published by his brother Laurence, titled *More Poems* (1936).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's *A Shropshire Lad* includes some iconic individual poems like "Loveliest of trees, the cherry now" (II), "When I was one-and-twenty" (XIII), "Is my team ploughing" (XXVII) and "Into my heart an air that kills" (XL).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His mother died on his twelfth birthday, and his father, a country solicitor, then married an elder cousin, Lucy, in 1873.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Two of his siblings became prominent writers, sister Clemence Housman and brother Laurence Housman.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman was educated at King Edward's School in Birmingham and later Bromsgrove School, where he revealed his academic promise and won prizes for his poems.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In 1877, he won an open scholarship to St John's College, Oxford, and went there to study classics.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Although introverted by nature, Housman formed strong friendships with two roommates, Moses John Jackson (1858–1923) and A.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Though Housman obtained a first in classical Moderations in 1879, his dedication to textual analysis led him to neglect the ancient history and philosophy that formed part of the Greats curriculum.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Accordingly, he failed the Finals and had to return humiliated in Michaelmas term to resit the exam so as to at least gain a lower-level pass degree.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Though some attribute Housman's unexpected performance in his exams directly to his unrequited feelings for Jackson, most biographers adduce more obvious causes.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman was indifferent to philosophy and overconfident in his exceptional gifts and he spent too much time with his friends.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He may also have been distracted by news of his father's desperate illness.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] After Oxford, Jackson went to work as a clerk in the Patent Office in London and he also arranged a job there for Housman.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The two shared a flat at 82 Talbot Road, Bayswater, with Jackson's brother Adalbert until 1885, when Housman moved to lodgings of his own, probably after Jackson responded to a declaration of love by telling Housman that he could not reciprocate his feelings.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Two years later, Jackson moved to India, placing more distance between himself and Housman.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] When he returned briefly to England in 1889 to marry, Housman was not invited to the wedding and knew nothing about it until the couple had left the country.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Adalbert Jackson died in 1892 and Housman commemorated him in a poem published as "XLII – A.J.J." of *More Poems* (1936).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Meanwhile, Housman pursued his classical studies independently, and published scholarly articles on Horace, Propertius, Ovid, Aeschylus, Euripides and Sophocles.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He also completed an edition of Propertius, which however was rejected by both Oxford University Press and Macmillan in 1885, and was destroyed after his death.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He gradually acquired such a high reputation that in 1892 he was offered and accepted the professorship of Latin at University College London (UCL).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] When, during his tenure, an immensely rare Coverdale Bible of 1535 was discovered in the UCL library and presented to the Library Committee, Housman (who had become an atheist while at Oxford) remarked that it would be better to sell it to "buy some really useful books with the proceeds".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Although Housman's early work and his responsibilities as a professor included both Latin and Greek, he began to specialise in Latin poetry.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] When asked later why he had stopped writing about Greek verse, he responded, "I found that I could not attain to excellence in both." In 1911 he took the Kennedy Professorship of Latin at Trinity College, Cambridge, where he remained for the rest of his life.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Between 1903 and 1930, Housman published his critical edition of Manilius's *Astronomicon* in five volumes.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He also edited Juvenal (1905) and Lucan (1926).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He was and may remain the last great textual critic".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In the eyes of Harry Eyres, however, Housman was "famously dry" as a professor, and his influence led to a scholarly style in the study of literature and poetry that was philological and without emotion.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Many colleagues were unnerved by Housman's scathing attacks on those he thought guilty of shoddy scholarship.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In his paper "The Application of Thought to Textual Criticism" (1921) he wrote: "A textual critic engaged upon his business is not at all like Newton investigating the motion of the planets: he is much more like a dog hunting for fleas".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He declared many of his contemporary scholars to be stupid, lazy, vain, or all three, saying: "Knowledge is good, method is good, but one thing beyond all others is necessary; and that is to have a head, not a pumpkin, on your shoulders, and brains, not pudding, in your head".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Gow, quoted examples of these attacks, noting that they "were often savage in the extreme".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Gow also related how Housman intimidated students, sometimes reducing the women to tears.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] According to Gow, Housman could never remember the names of female students, maintaining that "had he burdened his memory by the distinction between Miss Jones and Miss Robinson, he might have forgotten that between the second and fourth declension".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Among the more notable students at his Cambridge lectures was Enoch Powell, one of whose own Classical emendations was later complimented by Housman.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In his private life, Housman enjoyed country walks, gastronomy, air travel and making frequent visits to France, where he read "books which were banned in Britain as pornographic" but he struck A.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Benson, a fellow don, as being "descended from a long line of maiden aunts".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His feelings about his poetry were ambivalent and he certainly treated it as secondary to his scholarship.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He did not speak in public about his poems until 1933, when he gave a lecture "The Name and Nature of Poetry", arguing there that poetry should appeal to emotions rather than to the intellect.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His ashes are buried just outside St Laurence's Church, Ludlow.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] A cherry tree was planted there in his memory (see *A Shropshire Lad* II) and replaced by the Housman Society in 2003 with a new cherry tree nearby.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In the same vein, Harry Eyres interpreted it as "what you could see as an act of self-punishment" that so many years were devoted to "a minor Roman versifier whose long didactic poem on astrology must rank as one of the most obscure in the entire annals of poetry".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] During his years in London, Housman completed *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of 63 poems.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] After one publisher had turned it down, he helped subsidise its publication in 1896.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] At first selling slowly, it rapidly became a lasting success.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Its appeal to English musicians had helped to make it widely known before World War I, when its themes struck a powerful chord with English readers.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The book has been in print continuously since May 1896.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The poems are marked by pessimism and preoccupation with death, without religious consolation (Housman had become an atheist while still an undergraduate).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman wrote many of them while living in Highgate, London, before ever visiting Shropshire, which he presented in an idealised pastoral light as his 'land of lost content'.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman himself acknowledged that "No doubt I have been unconsciously influenced by the Greeks and Latins, but [the] chief sources of which I am conscious are Shakespeare's songs, the Scottish Border ballads, and Heine".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman began collecting a new set of poems after the First World War.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His early work was an influence on many British poets who became famous by their writing about the war, and he wrote several poems as occasional verse to commemorate the war dead.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] This included his *Epitaph on an Army of Mercenaries*, honouring the British Expeditionary Force, an elite but small force of professional soldiers sent to Belgium at the start of the war.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In the early 1920s, when Moses Jackson was dying in Canada, Housman wanted to assemble his best unpublished poems so that Jackson could read them before his death.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] These later poems, mostly written before 1910, show a greater variety of subject and form than those in *A Shropshire Lad* but lack its consistency.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He published his new collection as *Last Poems* (1922), feeling that his inspiration was exhausted and that he should not publish more in his lifetime.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] After Housman's death in 1936, his brother, Laurence published further poems in *More Poems* (1936), *A.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] E .H.: Some Poems, Some Letters and a Personal Memoir by his Brother* (1937), and *Collected Poems* (1939).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] H.* includes humorous verse such as a parody of Longfellow's poem *Excelsior*.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman also wrote a parodic *Fragment of a Greek Tragedy*, in English, first published in 1883 in *The Bromsgrovian*, the magazine of his old school, and frequently reprinted.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Sparrow himself adds, "How difficult it is to achieve a satisfactory analysis may be judged by considering the last poem in *A Shropshire Lad*.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Of its four stanzas, Housman tells us that two were 'given' him ready made; one was coaxed forth from his subconsciousness an hour or two later; the remaining one took months of conscious composition.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In 1942, Laurence Housman also deposited an essay entitled "A.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's 'De Amicitia'" in the British Library, with the proviso that it was not to be published for 25 years.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's homosexuality and his love for Moses Jackson.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Despite the conservative nature of the times and his own caution in public life, Housman was quite open in his poetry, and especially in *A Shropshire Lad*, about his deeper sympathies.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Poem XXX of that sequence, for instance, speaks of how "Fear contended with desire": "Others, I am not the first, / Have willed more mischief than they durst".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His poem "Oh who is that young sinner with the handcuffs on his wrists?", written after the trial of Oscar Wilde, addressed more general attitudes towards homosexuals.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] This refers to an old paraphrasing for homosexuality in English law.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry, especially *A Shropshire Lad*, was set to music by many British, and in particular English, composers in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The national, pastoral and traditional elements of his style resonated with similar trends in English music.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In 1904, the cycle *A Shropshire Lad* was set by Arthur Somervell, who in 1898 had begun to develop the concept of the English song-cycle in his version of Tennyson's "Maud".
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Stephen Banfield believes it was acquaintance with Somervell's cycle that led other composers to set Housman: Ralph Vaughan Williams is likely to have attended the first performance at the Aeolian Hall on 3 February 1905.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] His well-known cycle of six songs *On Wenlock Edge*, for string quartet, tenor and piano, was published in 1909.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Between 1909 and 1911, George Butterworth produced settings in two collections, *Six Songs from A Shropshire Lad* and *Bredon Hill and Other Songs*.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He also wrote the orchestral tone poem *A Shropshire Lad*, first performed at Leeds Festival in 1912.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Ivor Gurney was another composer who made renowned settings of Housman's poems.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Towards the end of World War I, he was working on his cycle *Ludlow and Teme*, for voice and string quartet (published in 1919), and went on to compose the eight-song cycle *The Western Playland* in 1921.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] One more who set Housman songs during this period was John Ireland in the song cycle, *The Land of Lost Content* (1920–21).
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Charles Wilfred Orr produced 24 Housman settings in songs and song cycles composed from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Even composers not directly associated with the 'pastoral' tradition, such as Arnold Bax, Lennox Berkeley and Arthur Bliss, were attracted to Housman's poetry.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Housman's attitude to musical interpretations of his poetry, and indeed to music in general, was either indifference or torment.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] He told his friend Percy Withers that he knew nothing of music and it meant nothing to him.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Withers once played him a record of the Vaughan Williams setting, but realised he had made a mistake when he saw the look of disgust on the poet's face.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Nevertheless, by 1976, a catalogue listed 400 musical settings of Housman's poems.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] As of 2024, Lieder Net Archive records 678 settings of 188 texts.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The earliest commemoration of Housman was in the chapel of Trinity College in Cambridge, where there is a memorial brass on the south wall.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The Latin inscription was composed by his colleague there, A.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Gow, who was also the author of a biographical and bibliographical sketch published immediately following his death.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] From 1947, University College London's academic common room was dedicated to his memory as the Housman Room.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Blue plaques followed later elsewhere, the first being on Byron Cottage in Highgate in 1969, recording the fact that *A Shropshire Lad* was written there.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] More followed, placed on his Worcestershire birthplace, his homes and school in Bromsgrove.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The latter were encouraged by the Housman Society, which was founded in the town in 1973.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Another initiative was the statue in Bromsgrove High Street, showing the poet striding with walking stick in hand.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The work of local sculptor Kenneth Potts, it was unveiled on 22 March 1985.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The blue plaques in Worcestershire were set up on the centenary of *A Shropshire Lad* in 1996.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] In September of the same year, a memorial window lozenge was dedicated at Poets' Corner in Westminster Abbey.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The following year saw the première of Tom Stoppard's play *The Invention of Love*, whose subject is the relationship between Housman and Moses Jackson.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] As the 150th anniversary of his birth approached, London University inaugurated its Housman lectures on classical subjects in 2005, initially given every second year then annually after 2011.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] The anniversary itself in 2009 saw the publication of a new edition of *A Shropshire Lad*, including pictures from across Shropshire taken by local photographer Gareth Thomas.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] Among other events, there were performances of Vaughan Williams's *On Wenlock Edge* and Ivor Gurney's *Ludlow and Teme* at St Laurence's Church in Ludlow.
[src:egg-hunt/a-e-housman] These lectures are listed by date of delivery, with date of first publication given separately if different.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Hallelujah is a transliteration of Hebrew: הַלְּלוּ יָהּ (*hal[lə]lū yāh*), which means "praise ye Jah!" (from הַלְּלוּ, "praise ye!" and יָהּ, "Jah").
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The word *hallēl* (הַלֵּל) in Hebrew means a joyous praise in song.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The second part, Yah, is a shortened form of YHWH (Yahweh or Jehovah in modern English).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] It has been suggested that the acclamation arises from and is an onomatopoeic rendition of the ancient tradition of ululation.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In the Hebrew Bible *hallelujah* is actually a two-word phrase, *hal(le)lu-Yah*, and not one word.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The first part, *hallelu*, is the second-person imperative masculine plural form of the Hebrew verb *hillel* (הִלֵּל).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] From Hebrew הַלְלוּ־יָהּ (haləlū-yāh) “praise Yah,” combining the plural imperative of הָלַל (“to praise”) with יָהּ, the short theophoric form of the Tetragrammaton.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The phrase "hallelujah" translates to "praise Jah/Yah", though it carries a deeper meaning as the word *hallel* in Hebrew means a joyous praise in song, to boast in God.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The second part, Yah, is a shortened form of YHWH, and is a shortened form of his name "God, Jah, or Jehovah".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The name ceased to be pronounced in Second Temple Judaism, by the 3rd century BC due to religious beliefs.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] However, it is sometimes rendered in non-Jewish sources as "Yahweh" or "Jehovah".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Septuagint translates Yah as *Kyrios* (the LORD, stylized in all-capitals in English), because of the Jewish custom of replacing the sacred name with "Adonai", meaning "my Lord".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The linguist Ghil'ad Zuckermann argues that the word *Hallelujah* is usually not replaced by a *praise God!* translation due to the belief in iconicity: the perception that there is something intrinsic about the relationship between the sound of the word and its meaning.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] It starts and concludes a number of Psalms.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Greek transliteration ἀλληλούϊα (*allēlouia*) appears in the Septuagint version of these Psalms, in Tobit 13:17 and 3 Maccabees 7:13, and four times in Revelation 19:1–6, the great song of praise to God for his triumph over the Whore of Babylon.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] It is this usage that Charles Jennens extracted for the Hallelujah Chorus in Handel's *Messiah*.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] This transliteration is the basis of the alternative Latin transliteration "Alleluia" that is also used by Christians.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The word "hallelujah" is sung as part of the Hallel Psalms (interspersed between Psalms 113–150).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In Tractate Shabbat of the Talmud, Rabbi Yose is quoted as saying that the Pesukei dezimra Psalms should be recited daily.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Psalms 145–150, also known as the Hallel of pesukei dezimra, are included to fulfill this requirement in the liturgy for the traditional Jewish Shacharit (morning) service.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In addition, on the three Pilgrimage Festivals, the new moon and Hanukkah, Psalms 113-118 are recited.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The latter psalms are known simply as Hallel with no additional qualification.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Psalms 146:10, ending with Halleluja, is the third and final biblical quotation in the Kedushah.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] This expanded version of the third blessing in the Amidah is said during the Shacharit and Mincha (morning and afternoon) services when there is a minyan present.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] For most Christians, "Hallelujah" is considered a joyful word of praise to God, rather than an injunction to praise him.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The word "Alleluia", a Latin derivative of the Hebrew phrase "Hallelujah" has been used in the same manner, though in Christian liturgy, the "Alleluia" specifically refers to a traditional chant, combining the word with verses from the Psalms or other scripture.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] At the Easter service and throughout the Pentecostarion, Christos anesti is used in the place where Hallelujah is chanted in the western rite expressing happiness.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In day-to-day situations, the expressions of "Hallelujah" and "Praise the Lord" are used by Christians as spontaneous expressions of joy, thanksgiving and praise towards God.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In contemporary worship services across denominational lines, the use of these jubilatory phrases require no specific prompting or call or direction from those leading times of praise and singing.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In Methodist worship, "Hallelujah!" is a frequently used ejaculatory prayer.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In Christian worship, Alleluia is used as a liturgical chant in which that word is combined with verses of scripture, usually from the Psalms.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] This chant is commonly used before the proclamation of the Gospel.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In Western Christianity, congregations commonly cease using the word *Alleluia* during the period of Lent but restore it into their services at Easter.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The form of praise "Alleluia" is used by Christians to thank and glorify God; it finds itself present in many prayers and hymns, especially those related to Eastertide, such as "Christ the Lord is Risen Today".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Hebrew word *Hallelujah* as an expression of praise to God was preserved, untranslated, by the Early Christians as a superlative expression of thanksgiving, joy, and triumph.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Thus it appears in the ancient Greek Liturgy of St.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] James, which is still used to this day by the Patriarch of Jerusalem and, in its Syriac recension is the prototype of that used by the Maronites.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Mark, we find this rubric: "Then follow *let us attend*, the Apostle, and the Prologue of the Alleluia." The "Apostle" is the usual ancient Eastern title for the Epistle reading, and the "Prologue of the Alleluia" would seem to be a prayer or verse before Alleluia was sung by the choir.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In the Roman Rite the word *Alleluia* is associated with joy and is especially favoured in Paschal time, the time between Easter and Pentecost, perhaps because of the association of the *hallel* (Alleluia psalms) chanted at Passover.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] During this time, the word is added widely to verses and responses associated with prayers, to antiphons of psalms, and, during the Octave of Easter and on Pentecost Sunday, to the dismissal at the end of Mass ("Ite missa est").
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] On the other hand, the word *Alleluia* is excluded from the Roman liturgy during Lent, often euphemistically referred to during this time as the "A-word".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In pre-1970 forms of the Roman Rite it is excluded also in the pre-Lenten Septuagesima period and in Masses for the Dead.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The term *Alleluia* is used also to designate a chant beginning and ending with this word and including a verse of scripture, in particular a chant to greet and welcome the Lord whose word will be proclaimed in the Gospel reading.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The choir or cantor then sings a verse taken from the Mass Lectionary or the *Roman Gradual*, after which the congregation again sings "Alleluia".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In Lent the verse alone is sung or the word *Alleluia* is replaced by a different acclamation taken from the *Gradual*, or a tract is sung.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] If singing is not used, the Alleluia and its verse may be omitted at any season.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The complex plainchant setting in the *Roman Gradual* requires a high degree of skill and is mostly used only in monasteries and seminaries.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] This melismatic Gregorian chant opens with the cantor singing "Alleluia".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The choir repeats it, adding to the final syllable a long melisma called a jubilus.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] (The *Liber Usualis* notates the repeat with the Roman numeral "ij" (2) and continues with the jubilus.) The cantor then sings the main part of the verse, and the choir joins in on the final line.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The cantor then repeats the opening Alleluia, and the choir repeats only the jubilus.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The music is generally ornate, but often within a narrow range.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Alleluia for Christmas Eve, for instance, has an ambitus of only a perfect fifth, a rather extreme example.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Alleluias were frequently troped, both with added music and text.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] It is believed that some early Sequences derived from syllabic text being added to the jubilus, and may be named after the opening words of the Alleluia verse.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Alleluias were also among the more frequently used chants to create early organa, such as in the Winchester Troper.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Alleluia and its verse is replaced during Lent and in the pre-1970 form of the Roman Rite Mass also during Septuagesima time by a Tract.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] On the other hand, during Eastertide the Gradual is replaced with an Alleluia chant, thus putting two such chants before the Gospel reading.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In the Eastern Orthodox, as well as Byzantine Rite Eastern Catholic and Eastern Lutheran Churches, after reading the Apostle (Epistle) at the Divine Liturgy, the Reader announces which of the Eight Tones the Alleluia is to be chanted in.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The response of the choir is always the same: "Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia." What differs is the tone in which it is sung, and the stichera (psalm verses) which are intoned by the Reader.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Alleluia is paired with the Prokeimenon which preceded the reading of the Apostle.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] There may be either one or two Alleluias, depending upon the number of Prokeimena (there may be up to three readings from the Apostle, but never be more than two Prokeimena and Alleluia).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Reader then chants the first sticheron of the Alleluia.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Reader then chants the second sticheron of the Alleluia.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] "Alleluia in the ____ Tone:" Then he immediately chants the first sticheron of the first Alleluia.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Reader then chants the second sticheron of the first Alleluia.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] "In the ____ Tone:" And he chants the first sticheron of the second Alleluia.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Among the Orthodox, the chanting of Alleluia does not cease during Lent, as it does in the West.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] This is in accordance with the Orthodox approach to fasting, which is one of sober joy.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] During the weekdays of Great Lent and certain days during the lesser Lenten seasons (Nativity Fast, Apostles' Fast, and Dormition Fast), the celebration of the Divine Liturgy on weekdays is not permitted.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] The Alleluia at Matins is not related to scripture readings or Prokeimena; instead, it replaces "God is the Lord..." It is sung in the Tone of the Week and is followed by the Hymns to the Trinity (*Triadica*) in the same tone (see Octoechos for an explanation of the eight-week cycle of tones).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] "God is the Lord..." would normally be intoned by the deacon, but since the deacon does not serve on days with Alleluia, it is intoned by the priest.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Alleluia is also chanted to a special melody at funerals, memorial services (Greek: *Parastas*, Slavonic: *Panikhida*), and on Saturdays of the Dead.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Again, it is chanted in place of "God is the Lord...", but this time is followed by the Troparia of the Departed.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] Gospel readings are appointed for other services as well, particularly those in the Trebnik.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] A number of these are preceded by an Alleluia, in the same manner as that chanted at the Divine Liturgy, though sometimes there are no stichera (psalm verses).
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] During the sacred mystery (Sacrament) of baptism, in addition to the Alleluia before the Gospel, the choir also chants an Alleluia while the priest pours the Oil of Catechumens into the baptismal font.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] In modern English, "Hallelujah" is frequently spoken to express happiness that a thing hoped or waited for has happened.
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] An example is its use in the song "Get Happy".
[src:egg-hunt/alleluia] "Hallelujah" was the winning song of the Eurovision Song Contest 1979, performed in Hebrew by Milk and Honey, including Gali Atari, for Israel.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] The prime member, the Cross, had been introduced to Christian art in the 4th century as the *crux invicta*, a symbol of victory.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] As a group, they have a long tradition in iconography, dating back to the 9th century; the Utrecht Psalter of 830 is an example, though the only one from the Early Middle Ages known to Gertrud Schiller.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] This reflected an increase in theological interest in the sufferings of Christ at the time.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] Relics of the most important items had a long history, dating back to the Empress Helena's discovery of the True Cross in the early 4th century.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] Relics claiming to be the Holy Lance, Holy Sponge, Holy Chalice and nails from the cross were all venerated well before 1000, and were to proliferate in later centuries.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] There was a wave of new relics in the West at the time of the Crusades, and a further wave as the Instruments became featured more prominently in devotional literature and practices in the 14th century.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] In art, the Instruments either surrounded an image of Christ in andachtsbilder subjects such as the Man of Sorrows, or might appear by themselves - often the image of Christ's face on the Veil of Veronica was the focal point of the image.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] In both cases, the purpose of the representations was to symbolize the sufferings of Christ during his Passion.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] They had the practical advantage for less accomplished artists of being much easier to represent than human figures, and were no doubt often treated as a subject an apprentice could be left to do.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] Possibly the earliest representation of the isolated instruments laid out across a space is in a drawing in a German manuscript of about 1175, where they are to one side of a Christ in Majesty.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] In devotional books they were sometimes, by the Late Middle Ages, shown one at a time, accompanying one of the many texts that devoted meditations in turn to the episodes in which each had been used, before culminating in a figure subject with Jesus.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] Miniature versions of the objects were attached to rosaries and crucifixes, and used as aids to contemplation of the suffering of Christ.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] Depictions of the Instruments of the Passion may include many combinations of those following (though the cross of Jesus is almost always represented).
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] The principal group of the Instruments appear in other contexts as well.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] The lance and sponge on a stick are held as though they are standards or weapons by the archangels flanking the throne of Christ in a 6th-century mosaic from Ravenna (now in the Bode Museum, Berlin), and are often shown in this way thereafter, especially in scenes of the Last Judgement.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] In Eastern Orthodox art they are often on or around the Hetoimasia or "empty throne" of judgement.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] The Crown of Thorns sometimes hangs alone on the cross; it has been suggested that the Celtic cross originated from this motif.
[src:egg-hunt/arma-christi] The minor Instruments generally did not develop a sufficient ability to be recognised and understood in this way, and appear only in groups.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] An **artos** (Ancient Greek: ἄρτος, "leavened loaf", "bread") is a loaf of leavened bread that is blessed during services in the Eastern Orthodox and Byzantine rite catholic churches.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] A large Artos is baked with a seal depicting the resurrection for use at Pascha (Easter).
[src:egg-hunt/artos] Smaller loaves are blessed during great vespers in a ritual called Artoklasia and in other occasions like feast days, weddings, memorial services etc.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] Near the end of the Paschal Vigil, after the Prayer Before the Ambo, a single large loaf of bread, the Artos, is brought to the priest.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] Depicted on the top of the Artos are either the symbol of Christ's victory over death—the Cross, surmounted by a crown of thorns—or the Resurrection of Christ.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The Artos symbolizes the physical presence of the resurrected Christ among the disciples.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The priest blesses the Artos with a special prayer and sprinkles it with Holy Water.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The Artos is then placed on a small table before the Iconostasis where it remains throughout Bright Week.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] It is customary, whenever the faithful enter the Temple, for them to kiss the Artos as a way of greeting the Risen Christ.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] On every day of Bright Week, after the Paschal Divine Liturgy (or, alternatively, after Paschal Matins), the Artos is carried in a solemn procession around the outside of the church.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] In monasteries, the Artos is carried to the Trapeza every day of Bright Week, where at the end of the festive meal, it is lifted in a ceremony called the Lifting of the Artos.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] On Bright Saturday, after the Divine Liturgy, the priest says another prayer over the Artos and it is then broken and distributed among the whole congregation along with the Antidoron.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The significance of the artos is that it serves to remind all Christians of the events connected with the Resurrection of Our Lord Jesus Christ.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] While still living on earth, the Lord called Himself the Bread of Life, saying: *I am the bread of life; he who comes to Me shall not hunger, and He who believes in Me shall never thirst* (John 6:35).
[src:egg-hunt/artos] After His Resurrection, more than once Jesus appeared to His disciples, ate before them and blessed their own food.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] For example, as evening fell on the first day of His Resurrection, He was recognized in Emmaus by two of His disciples as He blessed and broke bread (Luke 24:13–35).
[src:egg-hunt/artos] On the 40th day after His Resurrection, the Lord ascended into heaven, and His disciples and followers found comfort in their memories of the Lord: they recalled His every word, His every step and His every action.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] When they met for common prayer, they would partake of the Body and Blood of Christ, remembering the Last Supper.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] When they sat down to an ordinary meal, they would leave a place at the head of the table empty for the invisibly present Lord and would lay bread on that place.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The Artos may also be compared to the unleavened bread of the Old Testament, which the people of ancient Israel, after being delivered from their captivity in the land of Egypt, ate during the week of the Passover (Ex.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] It is a custom among Russian Orthodox Christians to this day to keep a portion of the artos throughout the year and with due reverence and faith to eat of it in time of illness or distress.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] This is eaten, often together with a drink of Holy Water, which had been blessed at the Feast of the Theophany of Our Lord.
[src:egg-hunt/artos] On feast days towards the end of vespers there is a blessing of loaves, wheat, wine, and oil, whereafter the priest breaks one of the loaves from which action the rite receives its name: *Artoklasia*, "breaking of bread".
[src:egg-hunt/artos] The loaves for the Artoklasia may be sealed (before baking) with a stamp (as are the Prosphora for the Divine Liturgy); such a seal may have an Icon of a saint on it, or it may be a simple cross—perhaps inscribed with a prayer on it, such as "May the Blessing of the Lord be upon us.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The Ascension of Jesus to Heaven as stated in the New Testament has been a frequent subject in Christian art, as well as a theme in theological writings.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The earliest direct depictions of the Ascension date to around the beginnings of the 5th century, often based on the Hand of God representations and by the 6th century the iconography had been established.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In many depictions, (and always in the Eastern Church) the Virgin Mary is at the center of the group of Apostles (representing the Church) who look upwards towards the ascending Jesus who usually signals a blessing with his right hand.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] New Testament scenes that appear in the Early Christian art of the 3rd and 4th centuries typically deal with the works and miracles of Jesus such as healings, the multiplication of the loaves or the raising of Lazarus.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Although versions of the subject of *Christ in Majesty*, which show the resurrected and ascended Christ in heaven, appear earlier, the Ascension itself is not depicted until about 400.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In early scenes Christ may be shown striding up a mountain, at times the Hand of God reaching from within the clouds to assist him.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] An ivory plaque in Munich with such a scene is usually dated around 400, and is possibly the earliest Ascension image.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] This was to remain the most common type in the West for several centuries, and for example is repeated in the Drogo Sacramentary some 450 years later (see gallery).
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The crucifixion scene is virtually unknown in the 5th century and rare until the 6th century.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] By the 6th century, however, more images of both the Crucifixion and the Ascension began to appear, perhaps as a result of the theological discussions of the late 4th and early 5th centuries.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] 586) include some of the earliest images of the Crucifixion and Ascension, and in their Ascension depictions the Virgin Mary occupies a central position among the Apostles; Christ appears in a mandorla above, accompanied by angels.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] This was to remain the standard Byzantine and Eastern Orthodox depiction.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] By the 6th century the iconography of the Ascension had been established and by the 9th century Ascension scenes were being depicted on domes of churches.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In some representations there may be no mountain and he may be climbing a mandorla, or be lifted towards Heaven in a mandorla by angels.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Sometimes the last two footprints of Christ on the rock are seen; these were shown to pilgrims at what is now the Chapel of the Ascension on the Mount of Olives in Jerusalem.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The scene may also include the Apostles, two men in white and the Virgin Mary.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The Ascension of Jesus is not the only depiction of ascension and other figures, such as John the Evangelist, have been separately depicted as ascending to Heaven, following a medieval story in the *Golden Legend*.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The name of the Assumption of Mary indicates that this was a passive transit; depictions in art often show her being carried up on a cloud by angels.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Ascension scenes fall naturally into two zones, an upper heavenly part and a lower earthly part.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The ascending Christ may be carrying a resurrection banner or make a sign of benediction with his right hand.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The blessing gesture by Christ with his right hand is directed towards the earthly group below him and signifies that he is blessing the entire Church.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In the left hand he may be holding a Gospel or a scroll, signifying teaching and preaching.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] From the Renaissance on the angels may not be present.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The earthly part of the Ascension depictions do not only represent those believed to have been present at the Ascension, but the entire Church.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In some Ascension depictions both Apostle Paul and the Virgin Mary may be present.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Given Paul converted to Christianity after the Ascension, and that the New Testament does not directly place the Virgin Mary at the Ascension, these depictions represent "the Church" rather than the specific individuals.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] In Orthodox icons the Virgin Mary is at the center and Christ can be depicted in a mandorla, supported by angels.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Christ may be crowned in many such depictions.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Given that the Gospels do not mention that the Virgin Mary was a witness to the Ascension, her presence of the Virgin Mary in 5th and 6th century depictions of the Ascension such as those in the Rabbula Gospels are an indication of the important role she played in the art of that period.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] This approximate composition was to become typical in the West by the Renaissance.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] The Eastern Orthodox portrayal of the Ascension is a major metaphor for the mystical nature of the Church.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Other scenes with a similar raised figure, that used similar compositions to the Ascension are the Assumption of Mary, rare until the late Middle Ages, the Transfiguration of Jesus, and from the Early Renaissance the Resurrection of Jesus, where he begins to be seen floating clear of the tomb.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus-in-christian-art] Perhaps the earliest surviving works to show this iconography of the Resurrection is the well-known fresco by Andrea da Firenze in the Spanish Chapel of the Basilica of Santa Maria Novella in Florence, which dates to 1366.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The **Ascension of Jesus** (anglicized from the Vulgate Latin: *ascensio Iesu*, lit.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] 'ascent of Jesus') is the Christian and Islamic belief that Jesus ascended to Heaven.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Christian doctrine, as reflected in the major Christian creeds and confessional statements, holds that Jesus ascended after his resurrection, where he was exalted as Lord and Christ, sitting at the right hand of God.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Islamic doctrine holds that Jesus directly ascended to heaven without dying or resurrecting.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Gospels and other New Testament writings imply resurrection and exaltation as a single event.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The ascension is "more assumed than described", and only Luke and Acts contain direct accounts of it, but with different chronologies.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In Christian art, the ascending Jesus is often shown blessing an earthly group below him, signifying the entire Church.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Feast of the Ascension is celebrated on the 40th day of Easter, always a Thursday; some Orthodox traditions have a different calendar up to a month later than in the Western tradition.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Lutheran Churches and the Anglican Communion continue to observe the Feast of the Ascension.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Certain Nonconformist churches, such as the Plymouth Brethren, do not observe the feast.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Although the ascension is an important article of faith in Christianity, only Luke and Acts contain direct accounts of it.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In the shorter ending of Mark, in Matthew, and in John, it is only implied or alluded to.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Gospels do not picture resurrection and ascension as clearly separated in time.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Other New Testament writings also imply resurrection and exaltation as a single event.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Various epistles (Romans 8:34, Ephesians 1:19–20, Colossians 3:1, Philippians 2:9–11, 1 Timothy 3:16, and 1 Peter 3:21–22) refer to an ascension without specifying details, seeming, like Luke–Acts and John, to equate it with the post-resurrection "exaltation" of Jesus to the right hand of God.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Luke and Acts appear to describe the same event but present quite different chronologies, the gospel placing it on the same day as the resurrection and Acts forty days afterwards; various proposals have been put forward to resolve the contradiction, but none have been found satisfactory.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] According to Dunn, the author of Acts separated the resurrection and ascension to put a limit on the number of resurrection appearances, effectively excluding Paul's conversion experience from the *bona fide* resurrection appearances.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Other scholars note that the biblical authors tended to conflate or compress different events and narrate them as one which was a literary theme seen in other ancient biographies to improve the narrative flow.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Such scholars caution against a strictly chronological reading.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In the first and second Jesus is claiming to be the apocalyptic "one like a Son of Man" of Daniel 7; the last has mystified commentators – why should Mary be prohibited from touching the risen but not yet ascended Christ, while Thomas is later invited to do so?
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The longer ending of Mark describes an ascension, but it may be a later addition to the original version of that gospel.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Ascension stories were fairly common around the time of Jesus and the evangelists, signifying the deification of a noteworthy person (usually a Roman Emperor), and in Judaism as an indication of divine approval.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Non-Jewish readers would have been familiar with the case of the emperor Augustus, whose ascent was witnessed by Senators; Romulus the founder of Rome, who, like Jesus, was taken to heaven in a cloud; the Greek hero Heracles (Hercules); and others.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In Christian theology, the death, resurrection, and exaltation of Jesus are the most important events, and a foundation of the Christian faith.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The early followers of Jesus believed that God had vindicated Jesus after his death, as reflected in the stories about his resurrection, ascension, and exaltation.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] This understanding is summarized by the theologian Justus Knecht who wrote: "Our Lord went up Body and Soul into heaven in the sight of His apostles, by His own power, to take possession of His glory, and to be our Advocate and Mediator in heaven with the Father.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The cosmology of the author of Luke–Acts reflects the beliefs of his age, which envisioned a three-part cosmos with the heavens above, an Earth centered on Jerusalem in the middle, and the underworld below.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Heaven was separated from the Earth by the firmament, the visible sky, a solid inverted bowl where God's palace sat on pillars in the celestial sea.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Humans looking up from Earth saw the floor of Heaven, made of clear blue lapis-lazuli (Exodus 24:9–10), as was God's throne (Ezekiel 1:26).
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In modern times, a literal reading of the ascension-stories has become problematic, due to the differences between the pre-scientific cosmology of the times of Jesus, and the scientific worldview that leaves no place for a Heaven above earth.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Theologian James Dunn describes the Ascension as at best a puzzle and at worst an embarrassment for an age that no longer conceives of a physical Heaven located above the Earth.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Yet, according to Dunn, a sole focus on this disparity is beside the real importance of Jesus' ascension, namely the resurrection and subsequent exaltation of Jesus.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Farrow notes that, already in the third century, the ascension-story was read by Origen in a mystical way, as an "ascension of the mind rather than of the body," representing one of two basic ascension theologies.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The real problem is the fact that Jesus is both present and absent, an ambiguity which points to a "something more" to which the Eucharist gives entry.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The same doctrine takes on another meaning for Muslims: most Islamic scholars hold that Jesus, the penultimate prophet of Islam, was not crucified or resurrected but his body directly ascended.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Feast of the Ascension is a major feast day of the Christian liturgical year, along with the Passion, Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Ascension Day is traditionally celebrated on the sixth Thursday after Easter Sunday, the fortieth day from Easter day, although some Catholic provinces have moved the observance to the following Sunday to facilitate the obligation to attend Mass.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Saint Jerome held that it was of apostolic origin, but in fact the Ascension was originally part of Pentecost (the coming of the Holy Spirit), and developed as a separate celebration only slowly from the late 4th century onward.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The feast was retained at the Protestant Reformation.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] It continues to be observed in Lutheran, Anglican, Methodist, and most Reformed churches.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Most of the Eastern Christian tradition (Eastern and Oriental Orthodox and some Eastern Catholic Churches, and the Church of the East), based on the Julian calendar, has a slightly different computation, up to a month later than in the Western tradition.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Other denominations, such as the Plymouth Brethren and Quakers, do not celebrate it as they do not adhere to the traditional Christian calendar of feasts.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] One of the Ascension hymns is Christ fuhr gen Himmel.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Ascension of Jesus has been a frequent subject in Christian art.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] By the 6th century, the iconography of the Ascension had been established and by the 9th century, ascension scenes were being depicted on domes of churches.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] 586) include some of the earliest images of the ascension.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Many ascension scenes have two parts, an upper (Heavenly) part and a lower (earthly) part.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The ascending Christ may be carrying a resurrection cross-banner or make a sign of benediction with his right hand.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In the left hand, he may be holding a Gospel or a scroll, signifying teaching and preaching.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] In many Eastern icons, the Virgin Mary is placed at the center of the scene in the earthly part of the depiction, with her hands raised towards Heaven, often accompanied by various Apostles.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The traditional site of the ascension is the Mount of Olives, on which the village of Bethany sits.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Before the conversion of Constantine the Great in 312 AD, early Christians honoured the ascension of Christ in a cave on the Mount, and by 384 the ascension was venerated on the present site, uphill from the cave.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] Around the year 390 a wealthy Roman woman named Poimenia financed construction of the original church called "Eleona Basilica" (*elaion* in Greek means "olive garden", from *elaia* "olive tree", and has an oft-mentioned similarity to *eleos* meaning "mercy").
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] This church was destroyed by Sassanid Persians in 614.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] It was subsequently rebuilt, destroyed, and rebuilt again by the Crusaders.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] This final church was later destroyed by Muslims, leaving only a 12×12 metre octagonal structure (called a *martyrium* – "memorial" – or "aedicule") that remains to this day.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The site was ultimately acquired by two emissaries of Saladin in the year 1198 and has remained in the possession of the Islamic Waqf of Jerusalem ever since.
[src:egg-hunt/ascension-of-jesus] The Russian Orthodox Church also maintains a convent of the ascension on the top of the Mount of Olives.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] It is one of the ecumenical (shared by multiple denominations) feasts of Christian churches, ranking with the feasts of the Passion and Pentecost.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The day of observance varies by ecclesiastical province in many Christian denominations, as with Lutherans and Catholics, for example.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The observance of this feast is of great antiquity.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Eusebius seems to hint at the celebration of it in the 4th century.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] At the beginning of the 5th century, Augustine of Hippo says that it is of Apostolic origin, and he speaks of it in a way that shows it was the universal observance of the Catholic Church long before his time.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Frequent mention of it is made in the writings of John Chrysostom, Gregory of Nyssa, and in the *Constitution of the Apostles*.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The *Pilgrimage of Aetheria* speaks of the vigil of this feast and of the feast itself, as they were kept in the church built over the grotto in Bethlehem in which Christ is traditionally regarded as having been born.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] It may be that prior to the 5th century the event narrated in the Gospels was commemorated in conjunction with the feast of Easter or Pentecost.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Some believe that the much-disputed forty-third decree of the Synod of Elvira (c.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] 300) condemning the practice of observing a feast on the fortieth day after Easter and neglecting to keep Pentecost on the fiftieth day, implies that the proper usage of the time was to commemorate the Ascension along with Pentecost.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Representations of the mystery are found in diptychs and frescoes dating as early as the 5th century.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Hymns for this feast are found in the Georgian Chantbook of Jerusalem, which contains material composed during the 5th century.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The Latin terms used for the feast, *ascensio* and, occasionally, *ascensa*, signify that Christ was raised up by his own powers, and it is from these terms that the holy day gets its name.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Book of Common Prayer of the Anglican Communion, "Holy Thursday" is listed as another name for Ascension Day.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In Western Christianity, the earliest possible date is 30 April (as in 1818 and 2285), or 1 May in some centuries (such as the 20th, 21st, and 22nd), while the latest possible date is 3 June (as in 1943 and 2038).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Catholic Church, the Ascension of the Lord is ranked as a Solemnity and is a Holy Day of Obligation.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Lutheran Churches, the Feast of the Ascension is a feast.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Anglican Communion, Ascension Day is a Principal Feast.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The three days before Ascension Thursday are sometimes referred to as the Rogation days, and the previous Sunday—the Sixth Sunday of Easter (or the Fifth Sunday *after* Easter)—as Rogation Sunday.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Ascension has a vigil and, since the 15th century, an octave, which is set apart for a novena of preparation for Pentecost.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Book of Common Prayer of the Church of England the Sunday following Ascension Day is called the Sunday after the Ascension.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] For Anglo-Catholics Ascension Day is a double of the 1st class with a privileged octave of the third order.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Catholic parishes in a number of countries that do not observe the feast as a public holiday have obtained permission from the Vatican to move observance of the Feast of the Ascension from the traditional Thursday to the following Sunday, the Sunday before Pentecost.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Similarly, the United Methodist Church allows the traditional celebration on Holy Thursday to be moved to Sunday.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] This is in keeping with a trend to move Holy Days of Obligation from weekdays to Sunday, to encourage more Christians to observe feasts considered important.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The decision to move a feast is made by each Conference of Catholic Bishops with prior approval of the Apostolic See.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In some cases the Conference may delegate the determination for specific feasts to the bishops of an ecclesiastical province within the conference, i.e. an archbishop and the neighbouring bishops.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the U.S., the determination of whether to move Ascension was delegated to the provinces by the USCCB: the ecclesiastical provinces which retain Thursday observance in 2022 are Boston, Hartford, New York, Omaha, Philadelphia, and the Personal Ordinariate of the Chair of Saint Peter.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] When celebrated on a Sunday, the earliest possible date is 3 May, and the latest is 6 June.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] In the Eastern Church this feast is known in Greek as *Analepsis*, the "taking up", and also as the *Episozomene*, the "salvation from on high", denoting that by ascending into his glory Christ completed the work of our redemption.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Ascension is one of the Twelve Great Feasts of the Orthodox liturgical year.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The feast is always observed with an All-night vigil.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The day before is the Apodosis (leave-taking) of Easter (i.e., the last day of the Feast of Easter).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Before the Vigil, the Paschal Hours are said for the last time and the Paschal greeting is exchanged.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] During the Polyeleos at Matins, the Epitaphios, which was placed on the altar on Holy Saturday (either at Matins or the Midnight Office, depending on local custom) is taken from the altar and carried in procession around the church.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] It is then put in the place reserved for it.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] At the Divine Liturgy, special antiphons are sung in place of Psalms 102 and 145 and the Beatitudes.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The Epistle is Acts 1:1–12, and the Gospel is Luke 24:36–53.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Ascension Thursday also commemorates the Holy Georgian Martyrs of Persia (17th–18th centuries).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Ascension has an Afterfeast of eight days.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The Sunday after Ascension is the Sunday of the Holy Fathers of the First Ecumenical Council at Nicaea.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The next day is appropriately a Saturday of the Dead (general commemoration of all faithful departed).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The Eastern Orthodox Church uses a different method of calculating the date of Easter, so the Eastern Orthodox commemoration of Ascension will usually be after the western observance (either one week, or four weeks, or five weeks later; but occasionally on the same day).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The earliest possible date for the feast is 13 May (of the Western calendar), and the latest possible date is 16 June.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Some of the Oriental Orthodox Churches, however, observe Ascension on the same date as the Western Churches.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The feast has been associated with specific hymns and other church music.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The oldest hymn in German related to the feast is the Leise "Christ fuhr gen Himmel", first published in 1480.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Johann Sebastian Bach composed several cantatas and the *Ascension Oratorio* to be performed in church services on the feast day.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] He first performed *Wer da gläubet und getauft wird, BWV 37*, on 18 May 1724, *Auf Christi Himmelfahrt allein, BWV 128*, on 10 May 1725, *Gott fähret auf mit Jauchzen, BWV 43*, on 30 May 1726 and the oratorio, *Lobet Gott in seinen Reichen, BWV 11*, on 19 May 1735.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Many Messianic psalms are used at the feast of Ascension including Psalm 24, Psalm 47 and Psalm 68.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The dialogue "Lift up your heads, O ye gates" from Psalm 24 (verses 7–10) has inspired Handel's setting in Part II of his *Messiah* in the scene "Ascension", and Christoph Bernhard Verspoell's 1810 hymn in German, "Öffnet eure Tore".
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Phillip Moore's anthem *The Ascension* sets words based on the same verses.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Olivier Messiaen wrote an orchestral suite, later partly transcribed for organ, called *L'Ascension* in the 1930s.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Settings of "God is gone up" have been composed by William Croft, Arthur Hutchings and Gerald Finzi (words by Edward Taylor).
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] Other settings suitable for the occasion include William Matthias's *Lift up your heads*.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] "Im Himmel hoch verherrlicht ist" (Highly gloryfied in Heaven) is a 1973 hymn in German for the occasion.
[src:egg-hunt/ascensiontide] The RSCM has produced an extensive list of music (including hymns, anthems and organ music) suitable for Ascension.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] An **egg hunt** is a treasure hunt played at Easter during which children look for hidden decorated eggs or Easter eggs.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Real hard-boiled eggs, which are typically dyed or painted, artificial eggs made of plastic filled with chocolate or candies, or foil-wrapped egg-shaped chocolates of various sizes are hidden in various places.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The food items found may be consumed with the end of the Lenten sacrifice during the preceding forty days of Lent.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The game is often played outdoors, but is also played indoors.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The children typically collect the eggs in a basket.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] When the hunt is over, prizes may be given out for various achievements, such as the largest number of eggs collected, for the largest or smallest egg, for the most eggs of a specific color, consolation prizes or booby prizes.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Real eggs may further be used in egg tapping contests.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] If eggs filled with confetti left from Mardi Gras (cascarones) are used, then an egg fight may follow.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Eggs are placed with varying degree of concealment, to accommodate children of varying ages and development levels.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] In South German folk traditions, it was customary to add extra obstacles to the game by placing them into hard-to reach places among nettles or thorns.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The egg was a symbol of the rebirth of the earth in pre-Christian celebrations of spring.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] However, the Easter egg itself was defined by early Christians as an Easter symbol of the resurrection of Jesus: the egg symbol was likened to the tomb from which Christ arose.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Hen's egg has played a role in Easter since the 4th century, and the tradition of decorated eggs may have arisen in Orthodox Christianity where eggs were stained red to signify the blood spilt by Christ.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The exchange of decorated eggs is known in many European countries such as Russia, and in England gifting of such eggs is known since the Middle Ages.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The specific custom of the Easter egg hunt may have its origin in Germany.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Some believed the Protestant Christian Reformer Martin Luther was the first to organize Easter egg hunts in the 16th century, when he suggested that men hide eggs in the garden for their wives and children to find.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The hunt for Easter eggs in the garden, representing the garden of Christ's tomb, symbolized searching the empty tomb and the risen Jesus.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The association of the Easter Bunny with Easter eggs has been known since at least the 17th century.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The German physician and botanist Georg Franck von Franckenau wrote in 1682 the folk belief of *der Oster-Hase* (Easter bunny) that laid *Hasen-Eier* (hare's-eggs) hidden in gardens, grass and bushes, and children then searched for these hidden eggs in egg hunts.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The tradition of Easter bunny and colored eggs was introduced into North America by migrants from southwest Germany in the 18th century.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The tradition of egg hunt was also introduced into the British royal household from Germany.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] When she was 14, Queen Victoria wrote about an egg hunt organised by her mother Duchess of Kent, who was born in Germany.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Queen Victoria and her husband Prince Albert also organised egg hunts for their children.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The eggs of the early period were likely hard-boiled and decorated, but artificial eggs also appeared in London in the 1850s.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The first chocolate eggs were made in France and Germany in the early 19th century, and in England chocolate Easter eggs were produced by Frys in 1873.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] The German origin of egg hunt was still noted in the late 19th century, A.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Reverend MaryJane Pierce Norton, Associate General Secretary of Leadership Ministries at the General Board of Discipleship, states that "there's something about going to hunt the eggs just as we might go to hunt for Jesus in the tomb.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] And when we find them it's that joy that the women had when they reached the tomb first and found that Jesus was no longer there." Traditionally the game is associated with Easter and Easter eggs, but it has also been popular with spring time birthday parties.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Egg hunts are a subject of the *Guinness Book of World Records*; Homer, Georgia, United States was listed in 1985 with 80,000 eggs to hunt in a town of 950 people.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] To enable children to take part in egg hunts despite visual impairment, eggs have been created that emit various clicks, beeps, noises, or music.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] A number of companies have made use of the popularity of Easter and more specifically Easter egg hunts to promote the sales of their candy products.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] Most notable have been chocolatiers including Cadbury with their annual Easter Egg Trail which takes place in over 250 National Trust locations in the UK.
[src:egg-hunt/egg-hunt] In 2015, the British chocolate company Thorntons worked with the geocaching community to hide chocolate eggs across the United Kingdom.
